<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98993045712629></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98993045712629><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=98993045712629>RE: What race???</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=98993045712629#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, May 15th 8:40 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have always played a Euridite mage.&nbsp;&nbsp;The key is not to stay in the Euridian newbie zone. It's very dark and obviously you have no night vision. Instead take a few minutes and take the boat to Qeynos. The newbie zone there is great and you can get up to slightly higher zone near by (Everfrost is the best kept secret in the game! You can level very quickly there solo).<br><br>Unlike other classes, the magi will quickly clear up the night blind issue. You will be night blind until you get your heatstone and coldstone. But .... other magi will give these to you, just ask nicely. I give them out all the time. It doesn't take long to get into your teens.<br><br>The advantage of the magi is the high Int. It means the not only will you have a high mana pool, but also that you will not need to buy as many int items so you can equip things that improve your resist or other stats.<br><br>For a new player that is concerned about being night blind and trying to learn the geography a high elf or gnome should be fine. You can make up the int in items later and you do get the ablity to see earlier.  For an experience player, however, I'd still vote for the Euridite.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
